The genus CopestylumMacquart, 1846 ( Diptera : Syrphidae : Eristalinae : Volucellini ) is by far the largest Neotropical radiation of Flower flies, with 400+ known species and it is likely that many more species are yet to be discovered and described ( Marinoni & Thompson 2003 ;
Rotheray et al . 2007
;
Montoya et al . 2012
; Montoya 2016 ).

In Colombia , the fauna of Copestylum is composed of 68 recorded species, in addition to fourteen species recognized as new to science but still undescribed. The genus is distributed in almost every thermal level from the high altitude paramos down to sea level, reaching the greatest diversity in the Andean and Amazonian regions of the country ( Restrepo-Ortiz & Carrejo 2009 ;
Montoya et al . 2012
; Montoya 2016 ). Copestylum is also diverse in Suriname , including 21 recorded species, in addition to six morphospecies denoted as SUR[ Suriname ] by Reemer (2016) . A total of 107 species of Copestylum have been recorded in the Brazilian Amazon ( Miranda 2017 ).

Larval stages of Copestylum are filter-feeding on microbes from detritus, developing on a huge array of aquatic or semi-aquatic environments rich in decaying plant materials, accelerating tissue recycling rates and water purification ( Seifert & Seifert 1979 ;
Rotheray et al . 2007
, 2009 ;
Ricarte et al . 2015
; Reemer 2016 ).

Adults of Copestylum occur in different environments, but most are found in primary tropical cloud forests and areas with undisturbed native vegetation, habitats where they can find humid environmental conditions such as phytotelmata, preferred breeding sites for most species in the genus ( Seifert & Seifert 1979 ;
Rotheray et al . 2007
, 2009 ;
Ricarte et al . 2015
).

The Amazonian rainforest is one of the most biodiverse, largest, and underexplored regions in the world. This region is recognized globally for its high concentration of endemism and unmatched species richness (

Myers 
et al
. 2000

; 
Haffer 2008
), but is among the ecosystems most threatened by global warming and increasing anthropogenic pressures, mainly due to large-scale metal mining, fracking, deforestation for timber extraction, as well as rampant arson of land around the rainforest to clear land for agriculture and the expansion of grazing crops for livestock or oil palm (
Salati 1985
; 
Fearnside 1993
; 
Vulinec 2000
; 

Myers 
et al
. 2000

; 

Colwell 
et al
. 2008

). These anthropogenic pressures have resulted in the fragmentation of the “forest ocean”, giving rise to small mosaics of isolated forest patches in which only a few remnants of primary vegetation remain, forming “islands in a sea of pastures” at an increasingly alarming and uncontrolled rate, that causes irreversible damage (
Smith 2021
), contrary to that occurs in the European Mediterranean and fragment Araucarian forest in 
Brazil
where open and disturbed habitats contribute to the maintenance of hoverfly diversity, suggesting the need for conserve mosaic landscapes (

Gittings 
et al
. 2006

; 

Meyer 
et al
. 2009

; 

Ricarte 
et al
. 2011

; 

de Souza 
et al
. 2014

). Despite the strategic importance of the Amazonian rainforest as a refuge for biodiversity and its high vulnerability, only a few flower fly groups have been properly inventoried and documented in this region (
Restrepo-Ortiz & Carrejo 2009
; 

Montoya 
et al
. 2012

; 
Reemer & Ståhls 2013
; 
Reemer 2016
; 
Montoya 2016
; 
Miranda 2014
, 
2017
; 

Carvalho-Filho 
et al
. 2019

).

