sec.p:
The description of C. enriquei sp. nov. based on a single male and two females reflects the difficulty of detecting and capturing this species, apparently restricted to Amazonian rainforests. Although we are unable to determine whether the species is really rare or simply difficult to detect, it is notable that the holotype was the only individual found amongst more than 2,363 Syrphidae specimens collected during an extensive six-month sampling, covering a great variety of habitats from lowland and foothills of the Amazon rainforest of Caquetá , Colombia ( 88,965 km ²). This sampling included different sampling methods, with 20 sampling stations distributed throughout the department (
Parada-Marín et al . 2021
). In the same way, only two specimens ( paratypes ) were captured in two localities in Suriname ( 163,820 km ²), despite having carried out an extensive sampling that covered above 50 localities (for details see Reemer 2016 ). Copestylum enriquei sp. nov. is hitherto known only from three localities in the Amazonian rainforests of Colombia and Suriname . Considering the gap between the three known localities where the new species occurs, it seems likely that the species is widespread in intermediate and adjacent areas within the Amazonian region of Brazil , Ecuador , Venezuela , and Peru .

Several syrphid species with restricted range have been described on the basis of few specimens ( Mengual 2013 ;
Morales et al . 2013
;
Montoya et al . 2017
; Montoya & Wolff 2020 ). In this regard,
Lim et al . (2012)
pointed out that “rare” species are common in taxonomic revisions and that collecting in the least explored areas may often lead to singletons becoming “double”, accompanied by the discovery of additional new species, based on “singletons” (
Montoya et al . 2021
), or the finding of new distributional records, with the expansion of geographic range such as the recent record of the rare species Cepa apeca Thompson, 2007 in the Colombian Andean-Amazonian region (
Parada-Marín et al . 2021
). In this sense, although nothing is known about the habitat preferences of C. enriquei sp. nov. , the discovery of new biological data about the breeding sites could explain its apparent rarity and restricted affinity to the Amazonian rainforest, critical to recognize its vulnerability and conservation status.

Most of the syrphid fauna of the Amazonian rainforest region is only known from one or a handful of locations ( Reemer & Ståhls 2013 ; Reemer 2016 ; Miranda 2014
, 2017 ;
Carvalho-Filho et al . 2019
), but it is not clear if they really have a restricted range or if their apparent rarity reflects the difficulty of sampling much of the isolated and difficult-to-access landscape that is predominant in the region. In this sense, the discovery of the new Copestylum species
further highlights the rich and unknown biodiversity of the Amazon rainforest suggesting also a high probability that more species might be discovered in this fragile, threatened, and unique ecosystem.
